<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>STANDARD INTRODUCTION FOR CONSULTATION RESPONSES ETC</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Mylius; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right; text-indent:27pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">    </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Written evidence from British Airways</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> (WRT 030)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:54pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:54pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">British Airways welcomes the opportunity to contribute to the Transport Select Committee’s inquiry into </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Winter Resilience in Transport.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">British Airways is one of the world’s leading global premium airlines and the UK’s largest international scheduled airline, carrying approximately 37 million passengers worldwide annually, on around 830 daily flights.  The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">airline employs around 40,000 people, the vast majority of these at its sites throughout the UK, and has an annual turnover of over £9 billion.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The airline’s two main operating bases are London’s Heathrow and Gatwick airports, with a smaller base at Londo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n City airport serving New York, European and domestic destinations.  From these three, British Airways flies over 280 aircraft to 173 destinations in more than 80 countries. In addition to passengers, the airline also transports cargo – more than 785,000 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tonnes of cargo are carried around the globe each year. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">British Airways’ main operating base, Heathrow, is one of the world’s busiest international airports. Unlike other major competitor hubs in Europe, Heathrow has been operating for many year</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s at full capacity throughout most of the day. It is further constrained by rigorous limits on night movements and restrictions on how the capacity of its two runways is maximised. Therefore it is vital that the impact of this operating environment is full</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y understood when considering the response of airlines and airport operators to winter weather disruption. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">While British Airways will continue to do everything in its power to minimise both the incidence and the impact of weather disruption, it is important to note that responsibility must lie with the airport operators and their service partners for ensuring t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hat the airport, including runways, taxiways, aprons, service roads and public access points to and from the airport, are resilient to adverse weather conditions. Heathrow Airport Limited and Gatwick Airport Limited, together with other airport operators, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">must continue to prioritise snow preparedness and provide timely, reliable and proactive responses both prior to, and during adverse weather events. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The impact of winter weather disruption on airport and airline operations is different for each event and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is highly dependent on the nature and duration of the adverse weather conditions. Despite robust contingency planning, airlines would never be able to guarantee operating a full schedule during times of significant weather disruption. This is particularly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the case at capacity constrained airports on the British Airways network, especially Heathrow. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It should be noted that Heathrow is not the only airport affected by winter weather disruption. In fact most UK airports, including Gatwick and London City, a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd many in Western Europe, including Paris, Frankfurt and Amsterdam, also suffer disruption during adverse winter weather conditions. However disruption at Heathrow is usually a result of a complex set of factors, key among which is the challenge presented</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by attempting to recover following any operational disruption at an airport which is operating at full capacity. At peak periods of travel demand, the capability for airlines to re-book and reaccommodate disrupted customers is more challenging and does ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ve a more detrimental customer impact for a longer duration.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">British Airways has a significant operating presence at three of the key London Airports – Heathrow, Gatwick and London City – and any disruption will therefore have a disproportionate impact on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the airline’s operations. This is especially the case at Heathrow where British Airways is the hub carrier.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Since 2010 British Airways has committed significant resources to planning and preparing for adverse winter weather conditions and the airline has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> held a company-wide review of its disruption planning process. In 2013 British Airways is investing over £18 million in improving its customers’ experience during times of disruption, and ensuring that British Airways staff can be mobilised effectively to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> deal with such disruption. The investment consists of developing new tools and technologies, as well as improving our training and processes.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">British Airways is committed to improving the experience for its customers during disruption and their welfare i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s extremely important to us. The airline has put in place improved resilience and contingency measures to deal with severe weather conditions through its Disruption Management Programme. British Airways is also working closely with the key airport operator</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s and service par</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tners to ensure that they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> also</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> suitably prepared to provide welfare support for our customers during disruption. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How resilient are the UK’s transport networks (including road, rail and air) to adverse winter weather?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is vital that airport operators, airlines, surface transport providers, and government agencies co-ordinate more effectively to ensure that where transport is affected by adverse weather, the impact on passengers is minimised. For example, where airline</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> operations are disrupted and airlines have the opportunity to recover by extending operations late into the night, it is vital that services such as surface transport provision and immigration facilities remain operational in order to minimise the risk of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> further disruption to customers. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What lessons have been learned since the severe weather experienced in the winter of 2009-10?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">British Airways cannot comment on the broader lessons learned by the wider transport sector, but the following lessons have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">informed the specific approach taken by the airline since the severe weather experienced in 2009-2010, as well as disruption experienced in subsequent winters.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">To improve communications to our customers through all available channels during disruption</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> – t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he feedback we received from customers su</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ggested that there is a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> need to ensure systems that display critical operational information are set up in the most effective way, and that there is a desire for earlier notification of cancellations or delays commu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nicated through more channels. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">3.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">To offer customers choice/options when their journey has been disrupted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> – an improved</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> approach to dealing with rebooking and refunds has been implemented.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">3.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Need for Improved operational planning and delivery during periods of disruption </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">– the effectiveness of the Heathrow Air Traffic Management Demand and Capacity Balancing group (HADACAB) - which is responsible for deciding on the percentage reduction of fli</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ghts needed to deal with expected disruption - and the consistency in the Met Office weather forecasting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> indicated that these are on-going issues and more development work needs to be done. In the past, the lack of an agreed multi-lateral schedule red</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">uction and the success rate of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Met Office to forecast the severity of weather were major contributing factors to disruption. In addition, the prolonged closure of both of the runways at Heathrow for snow sweeping has had a material impact on delivering</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the operation. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(Please see 6.1 for further details regarding HADACAB).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">3.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">To review and revise our command and control processes and procedures, including training</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> – for example</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the operational triggers that indicate the most appropriate level of command a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd escalation needed to be revisited. As a result</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a revised Crisis Management Process has now been implemented. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">3.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Providing customer facing colleagues</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> enhanced training and tools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> – a review of British Airway’s ‘Customer Support Programme’ proposition</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and communication was necessary to ensure colleagues are motivated, well briefed and intelligently deployed to assist our customers during times of disruption.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">3.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Increased regularity of process and procedure exercises –</span><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">British Airways has now implemented </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">more regular and cross-company exercises to improve its ability to respond in a real situation.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What practical changes have been made to ensure the UK is now better equipped to deal with severe weather?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Heathrow Airport is British Airways’ main </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">operating base and any disruption at this airport is likely to have an impact on all of its operations – because of this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Heathrow is the main focus in this section.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">4.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The airline has undertaken a full review of its response to severe weather disruption in order to introduce improvements that will help to minimise the negative impact on its passengers. As part of this review the airline has looked at the ways other compa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nies help their customers during times of disruption and listened to feedback from both customers and colleagues. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">      </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Winter Resilience</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">4.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Since 2010 British Airways has expanded its de-icing capability, investing in a significant amount of new equipment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to the value of more than £6 million. In addition, the airline is developing a safe and reliable de-icing operation at Heathrow to ensure this is not a limiting factor in any adverse winter weather conditions to departing aircraft, for example, by:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Introd</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ucing a dedicated Winter Operations Team; </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Providing further training for de-icing operatives;</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Agreeing a renewed third party de-icing contract for Terminal 1 and to provide contingency elsewhere at Heathrow if required;  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Purchasing of new fan blade de</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-icing equipment and de-icing simulators for training;</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">De-icing trials for new aircraft types (B787 and A380);</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin: